                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 511. 4A1/927.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Ambassador <persName type="to">Reid</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-12-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 9, 1910</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1431.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The department acknowledges the receipt of your
                    cablegram of the 2d instant, in which you state that the foreign office has
                    informed you that in order to obtain the necessary data in regard to morphine
                    and cocaine it has been found necessary to introduce a compulsory declaration in
                    Great Britain with regard to the quantities and value of imports and exports of
                    the drugs; that the compulsory declaration will go into operation on January 1
                    next, and that consequently several months must elapse before the desired
                    statistics can be gathered and considered representative of the ordinary course
                    of trade.</p>
                <p>Those Governments interested in the forthcoming opium conference have been
                    informed of the action taken by the British Government in accordance with its
                    proposals that there should be a preliminary study of the manufacture and trade
                    in morphine and cocaine before the conference.</p>
                <p>I am, sir, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
